			<a class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-btn" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapseSummary1792" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseSummary1792" data-lexicon-show="show" data-lexicon-hide="hide">
				abstract
			</a>
			<div class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse collapse" id="collapseSummary1792">
				<div class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-inner">
					<p>The review of the book <em>The Chernobyl Herbarium. Fragments of an Exploded Consciousness</em> by Michael Marder and Anaïs Tondeur. The author addresses the question of non-human forms of knowledge. Treating the disaster at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant as the first symptom of the crisis of cognition in the Anthropocene era, the author examines how the plants contained in the book are an example of co-creating with humans the representations and memories of (environmental) traumatic events.</p><p>keywords: Chornobyl; photography; posthumanism</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		
</li><li class="c-issue-toc__article c-issue-toc__article--no-translation" data-aricle-no="01">
